Derivative of inverse, eigenvalues and singular values #  Introduction #  Question: Given an invertible matrix $ A $, how can we find derivatives of:
 $ A^{-1} $: which denotes inverse matrix of $ A $ $ \lambda $: which denotes eigenvalues of $ A $ $ \sigma $: which denote singular values of $ A $  Let&rsquo;s start to find the formula for each case.
Finding derivative of inverse matrix #  Problem: Given matrix $ A $ subjected to variable $ t $: $  rac{dA}{dt} $, finding $  rac{A^{-1}}{dt} $
With two invertible matrices $ A, B $, we have
$ B^{-1} - A^{-1} = B^{-1}(A - B)A^{-1} $
We can pick any abitrary invertible matrix $ B $. Let takes $ B = A + 
abla A $ and place in the above formula, we have:
$$  egin{align*} &amp; (A + 
abla A)^{-1} - A^{-1} = (A + 
abla A)^{-1}(A - B)A^{-1} 
ewline \leftrightarrow \quad &amp;  rac{
abla A^{-1}}{
abla t} = -(A + 
abla A)^{-1}( rac{
abla A}{
abla t})A^{-1} \end{align*} $$
And as $ 
abla t 	o 0 $, we have:
$$  egin{align*} &amp; \lim_{
abla t 	o 0 \leftrightarrow 
abla A 	o 0 }  rac{
abla A^{-1}}{
abla t} = \lim_{
abla t 	o 0 \leftrightarrow 
abla A 	o 0 } - (A + 
abla A)^{-1}( rac{
abla A}{
abla t})A^{-1} 
ewline \leftrightarrow \quad &amp; \lim_{
abla t 	o 0 \leftrightarrow 
abla A 	o 0 }  rac{
abla A^{-1}}{
abla t} = \lim_{
abla t 	o 0} - (A)^{-1}( rac{
abla A}{
abla t})A^{-1} \end{align*} $$
This is equivalent to definition of derivative of matrix $ A^{-1} $. So the final answer is:
$$  rac{d A^{-1}}{dt} = - A^{-1} rac{dA}{dt}A^{-1} $$
Derivative of eigenvalue $ \lambda $ #  Problem: Given matrix $ A $ subjected to variable $ t $, find $  rac{d \lambda }{dt} $, where $ \lambda $ is eigenvalue of matrix $ A $.
Recalling there are two type of eigenvectors: left and right. The below table shows formula on relationship between eigenvalue $ \lambda $, eigenvector $ x $ and the original matrix $ A $
   Form Left Right     vector $ y^TA = \lambda y^T $ $ Ax = \lambda x $   matrix $ Y^TA = \Lambda Y^T $ $ AX = X \Lambda $    And: $ Y^TX = I $
Using those formula with a function of $ t $, we have:
$$  egin{align*} &amp; y^T(t) A(t) x(t) = \lambda (t) y^T(t) x(t) 
ewline \leftrightarrow \quad &amp; \lambda (t) = y^T(t) A(t) x(t) \end{align*} $$
So calulate derivative, with note that $ y^T(t)x(t) = I $
$$  egin{align*}  rac{d \lambda}{dt} &amp; =  rac{d y^T}{dt} A x(t) + y^T(t)  rac{d A} {dt} x(t) + y^T(t) A(t)  rac{d x}{dt} 
ewline &amp; = ( rac{d y^T}{dt} A x(t) + y^T(t) A(t)  rac{d x}{dt} ) + y^T(t)  rac{d A} {dt} x(t) 
ewline &amp; = \lambda (t) ( rac{d y^T}{dt} x(t) + y^T(t) rac{d x}{dt}) + y^T(t)  rac{d A} {dt} x(t) 
ewline &amp; = 0 + y^T(t)  rac{d A} {dt} x(t) 
ewline &amp; = y^T(t)  rac{d A} {dt} x(t) 
ewline \end{align*} $$
So the final answer is:
$$  rac{d \lambda}{dt} = y^T(t) rac{dA}{dt}x(t) $$
Derivative of $ \sigma $ #  Problem: Given matrix $ A $ subjected to variable $ t $, finding $  rac{d(\sigma)}{d(t)} $, which denotes singular values of matrix $ A $.
Recall that $ A $ can be written as SVD form as $ A = U^T \Sigma V $, where $ U^T $, $ V $ are orthogonal matrices, and $ \Sigma $ is symmetric matrix which contains singular values in diagonal line.
$$  egin{align*} A = U \Sigma V^T \leftrightarrow \Sigma = U^TAV \end{align*} $$
With a any $ \sigma $ in $ \Sigma $, we have:
$$  egin{align*}  rac{d \sigma}{dt} &amp; =  rac{d(u^TAv)}{dt} 
ewline &amp; =  rac{du^T}{dt}Av + u^T rac{dA}{dt}v + u^TA rac{dv}{dt} 
ewline &amp; =  rac{du^T}{df}u\sigma + u^T rac{dA}{dt}v + \sigma v^T rac{dv}{dt} \end{align*} $$
Recall that $ u^Tu = 0 $ and $ v^Tv = 0 $ since $ u, v $ are orthogonal. Therefore:
$$  egin{align*}  rac{d \sigma}{dt} &amp; =  rac{du^T}{df}u\sigma + u^T rac{dA}{dt}v + \sigma v^T rac{dv}{dt} 
ewline &amp; = 0 + u^T rac{dA}{dt}v + 0 
ewline &amp; = u^T rac{dA}{dt}v \end{align*} $$
So the final answer is:
$$  rac{d \sigma}{dt} = u^T rac{dA}{dt}v $$
